Package se.arkalix.net.http.consumer

Class HttpConsumer

  • java.lang.Object
    • se.arkalix.net.http.consumer.HttpConsumer
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    ArConsumer
    public class HttpConsumer
extends java.lang.Object
implements ArConsumer
    Client useful for consuming an secure or insecure HTTP service.

    This class provides similar functionality to HttpClient, with the exception that hostnames, encodings, authorization tokens and other details are managed automatically.

    • Constructor Detail

      • HttpConsumer

        public HttpConsumer​(HttpClient client,
                    ServiceDescription service)
        Creates new consumer configured to support att encodings returned by EncodingDescriptor.dtoEncodings().
        Parameters:
        client - HTTP client to use for consuming service.
        service - Service to consume.
        Throws:
        java.lang.NullPointerException - If client or service is null.
        java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - If client is configured to use HTTPS and the ServiceDescription.security() method of the given service returns SecurityDescriptor.NOT_SECURE, or if client is configured to use plain HTTP and the given service is secure returns any other security/access policy than SecurityDescriptor.NOT_SECURE.
        java.lang.IllegalStateException - If service does not support any interface triplet compatible with the given client and any one out of the default DTO encodings.

      • HttpConsumer

        public HttpConsumer​(HttpClient client,
                    ServiceDescription service,
                    java.util.Collection<EncodingDescriptor> encodings)
        Creates new consumer.
        Parameters:
        client - HTTP client to use for consuming service.
        service - Service to consume.
        encodings - Supported request/response encodings. If specified as null, the encodings returned by EncodingDescriptor.dtoEncodings() are used.
        Throws:
        java.lang.NullPointerException - If client or service is null.
        java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - If client is configured to use HTTPS and the ServiceDescription.security() method of the given service returns SecurityDescriptor.NOT_SECURE, or if client is configured to use plain HTTP and the given service is secure returns any other security/access policy than SecurityDescriptor.NOT_SECURE.
        java.lang.IllegalStateException - If service does not support any interface triplet compatible with the given client and any one out of the given encodings.
